The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Saturday, August 21, 2004 				 Boost to Lefts PF hopes
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Aug. 20: Left parties and trade unions have got support from a parliamentary committee over their demand to increase the provident fund interest rate.																								The committee tabled its report in Parliament today, recommending that the government at least maintain status quo  that is continue with 9.5 per cent interest  till it takes a final decision.																								The central board of provident fund trustees had at its fourth meeting on August 9 settled for 8.5 per cent, overruling protests from the Left and the trade unions.																								Union labour minister Sis Ram Ola, however, had held out some hope for the protesters when he said the decision was interim and the government would take a final decision at the end of the year.																								The parliamentary standing committee report said: The government should protect the interest of the subscribers while taking a decision. And the government should maintain a status quo till it takes a final decision.																								It also expressed deep concern at the interest slash, which would affect 3 crore subscribers.																								In another boost to the Left and its affiliates, the committee said the board of trustees should have taken a decision on the basis of consensus. 																								The central board of provident fund trustees had decided to go by the opinion of the majority of its 42 members on August 9 after they failed to arrive at a consensus. 
